.TH HELLO 1 "" "" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hello \- print a top-level message
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hello
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hello
is a small command-line program that prints a top-level message and exits.
Its source was recovered from the ELF binary
.IR hello-gcc-O2 .
The recovered project is organized as C source files but reflects a
binary originally linked against the C++ standard library: it contains
a destructor helper for
.BR std::vector<std::string> ,
iostream support shims for stream newline /
.BR std::endl
and ctype widening, iostream global initialization, and the usual CRT
startup and constructor/destructor glue.
.PP
Program flow begins in the CRT startup stub, which transfers control to
the entry point defined in
.IR src/main.c ;
that entry point performs the top-level message printing and returns.
.SH OPTIONS
.B hello
does not define any required options. Any
.I OPTIONS
shown in the synopsis are accepted only in the generic sense that the
program is invoked from the command line; no flags are documented by
the recovered sources.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cmake (1),
.BR cc (1),
.BR ld (1)
